====== RustFS KMS Encryption Setup Guide ======

This guide walks you through configuring RustFS with HashiCorp Vault for server-side encryption (SSE-KMS) using the Houston S3 Browser Cockpit plugin. The entire process is managed through the web interface.

===== Video Walkthrough =====

A narrated video walkthrough is available: [[rustfs-kms-guide.mp4|rustfs-kms-guide.mp4]]

----

===== Prerequisites =====

  * RustFS server installed and running (binary at ''/usr/local/bin/rustfs'', systemd unit ''rustfs.service'')
  * HashiCorp Vault server with a KV v2 secrets engine
  * A KMS provider configured in the Control Plane
  * A ''kv2_rustfs'' key policy created in the Control Plane
  * Cockpit with the Houston S3 Browser plugin installed

----

===== 1. Connect to RustFS =====

Open Cockpit and navigate to the **S3 Browser** plugin. On the Connections page, locate your RustFS endpoint and click **Connect**. The backend is automatically detected as RustFS.

{{:rnd:matt-encryption:houston-s3-browser:rustfs-kms:01-connections-list.png|Connections List}}

----

===== 2. View Buckets =====

After connecting, the **Buckets** tab displays your storage buckets. Notice the **RustFS KMS Setup** tab in the navigation — this tab only appears for RustFS-backed connections.

{{:rnd:matt-encryption:houston-s3-browser:rustfs-kms:02-buckets-view.png|Buckets View}}

----

===== 3. Check KMS Status (Unconfigured) =====

Click the **RustFS KMS Setup** tab. The Service Status panel shows:
  * **Binary**: Installed
  * **Service**: Running
  * **Config File**: Present
  * **KMS**: Disabled

Below the status is the **Configure RustFS KMS (Vault)** section.

{{:rnd:matt-encryption:houston-s3-browser:rustfs-kms:03-kms-unconfigured.png|KMS Unconfigured}}

----

===== 4. Configure KMS =====

  - **Select KMS Provider** from the dropdown — this automatically fills the Vault address
  - **Select Default Key ID** from the available key policies (e.g., ''rustfs-encryption'')
  - **Vault Token** is optional when a provider is selected — credentials are supplied via AppRole

{{:rnd:matt-encryption:houston-s3-browser:rustfs-kms:04-form-filled.png|Form Filled}}

----

===== 5. Enable KMS =====

Click **Enable KMS** to apply the configuration. The system:
  - Writes Vault environment variables to ''/etc/default/rustfs''
  - Sets ''RUSTFS_KMS_ENABLE=true''
  - Configures the Vault address and token
  - Restarts the RustFS service

A green confirmation message appears when successful.

{{:rnd:matt-encryption:houston-s3-browser:rustfs-kms:05-kms-enabled-result.png|KMS Enabled}}

----

===== 6. Verify Configured Status =====

After configuration, the Service Status panel shows everything healthy:
  * **Binary**: Installed
  * **Service**: Running
  * **Config File**: Present
  * **KMS**: Enabled

The detail row shows the Vault backend, address, default key ID, and confirms the token is set.

{{:rnd:matt-encryption:houston-s3-browser:rustfs-kms:06-configured-status.png|Configured Status}}

----

===== 7. Enable Bucket Encryption =====

Switch to the **Buckets** tab. With KMS configured, you can now enable server-side encryption on individual buckets.

{{:rnd:matt-encryption:houston-s3-browser:rustfs-kms:07-buckets-after-setup.png|Buckets After Setup}}

Click the three-dot menu (⋮) on a bucket row and select **Set Encryption**. In the modal:
  * **Algorithm**: Choose ''SSE-KMS'' for Vault-backed encryption
  * **KMS Key Policy**: Select from available key policies (e.g., ''rustfs-encryption'')

Click **Apply** to enable encryption on the bucket.

{{:rnd:matt-encryption:houston-s3-browser:rustfs-kms:08-set-encryption-modal.png|Set Encryption Modal}}

----

===== 8. Upload Files =====

Navigate into the encrypted bucket. Any files uploaded will be encrypted at rest using the Vault-managed key. The encryption is transparent — files are encrypted automatically on write and decrypted on read.

{{:rnd:matt-encryption:houston-s3-browser:rustfs-kms:09-object-encryption-info.png|Files in Encrypted Bucket}}

----

===== Troubleshooting =====

^ Issue ^ Resolution ^
| KMS shows "Disabled" after Enable | Check that Vault is reachable from the RustFS host and the token is valid |
| "Failed to create service token" | Verify the AppRole credentials in the Control Plane are correct |
| Enable KMS button stays disabled | Select both a KMS provider and a default key ID |
| Bucket encryption fails | Ensure KMS is enabled and RustFS was restarted after configuration |
| "No kv2_rustfs policies found" | Create a ''kv2_rustfs'' key policy in the Control Plane for your provider |

----
